able position;\n\n==Sponsorship==\n'''Title Sponsor'''\n* [[KFC]]\n* [[Rebel (company)|Rebel]] ([[Women's Big Bash League|WBBL]])\n\n'''Associate Sponsor'''\n* [[Weet-Bix]]\n* [[Toyota]]\n* [[Extra (gum)|Wrigley Extra]]\n* [[Commonwealth Bank]]\n* [[Balkrishna Industries|BKT Tires]]\n* [[Woolworths Supermarkets|Woolworths]]\n* [[Dream11]]\n\n'''Apparel Sponsor'''\n* [[Majestic Athletic]] (Team Apparel)\n* [['47 (brand)|'47]] (Caps/Hats)\n\n'''Broadcast Partners'''\n* [[Fox Cricket]]\n* [[Seven Network]]\n* [[Radio Australia]] (Outside Australia)\n* [[Macquarie Sports Radio 954|Macquarie Sports Radio]]\n* [[Crocmedia]] ([[1116 SEN]])\n\n==Salary cap==\n\n[[File:Big Bash League Logo.svg|thumb|BBL old logo used up to 2014\u201315 season|150px]]\nThe salary cap was initially $1 million, and increased to $1.05 million for the third season.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/big-bash-tweaks-player-rules-20130612-2o3am.html Big Bash tweaks player rules] smh.com.au. Retrieved on 3 December 2015.</ref> In February 2015, the salary cap increased to $1.3 million for the fifth season,<ref name=\"cricketbadger1\"/> and to $1.6 million for the sixth season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bigbash.com.au/news/big-bash-league-kfc-bbl-squads-playing-list-salary-cap-guidelines-updated-bbl07/2017-08-09 |title=Updated BBL07 squads for each team |publisher=Cricket Australia |author=Kanoniukm, Callum |date=9 August 2017 |accessdate=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Prize money==\n[[Cricket Australia]] increased the prize money for the BBL to a total of $890,000 for the four finalists from [[2015\u201316 Big Bash League season|2015\u201316 season]], after the [[Champions League Twenty20]] tournament was discontinued with effect from 2015. The prize money will be split between the teams as follows:<ref name=\"prize money\">[http://www.bigbash.com.au/news/cricket-australia-increase-big-bash-league-prize-money-after-no-clt20/2015-12-15 CA INCREASE BBL|05 PRIZE POOL] bigbash.com.au. Retrieved on 15 December 2015</ref>\n\n*$20,000 \u2013 To the team finishing fifth in the season\n*$80,000 \u2013 To each losing semi-finalist\n*$260,000 \u2013 To the [[#Tournament_results|Runner up]] \n*$450,000 \u2013 To the [[#Tournament_results|Champion]] of the season\n\nHowever, the additional cash increase of $600,000 will go to successful clubs and not their players. Up to the [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|2014\u201315 BBL season]], a total prize money of $290,000 was awarded.<ref name=\"prize money\" />\n\n==Audience==\n\n===Attendance===\n[[File:Melbourne Stars vs Hobart Hurricanes, BBL 05.jpg|thumb|240px|Melbourne Stars vs Hobart Hurricanes at the MCG on 6 January 2016]]\nAverage home crowds for the regular season are listed below. These figures do not include finals matches. The figures for the whole season average include the finals.<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/cricket/big-bash-league-infant-tournament-now-part-of-australian-crickets-summer-fabric/news-story/98897cf3111da3cb16f6fd9e6744e101 Big Bash League: Infant tournament now part of Australian cricket's summer fabric] heraldsun.com.au. Retrieved on 25 November 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.adelaidestrikers.com.au/news/crowd-records-tumble-at-strikers-semi-final/2015-01-25 Crowd Records Tumble at Strikers Semi-Final], adelaidestrikers.com.au. Retrieved on 25 November 2015.</ref> Post-Christmas matches have historically been the highest attended period for the League.<ref name=\"BBL5 schedule\">[http://www.cricket.com.au/news/bbl05-big-bash-league-fixture-release-2015-16-final-host-highest-qualifying-team-all-matches-live/2015-07-12 Big Bash League schedule released] cricket.com.au. Retrieved on 25 November 2015.</ref> BBL has provided a platform to create interest in playing cricket among younger children, due to its big hitting, high scoring and entertaining nature of the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-12-22/hinds:-even-test-purists-must-see-the-bright-side-of-the-bbl/9278950 |title=Big Bash League winning over Test cricket purists as kids embrace the game |author=Hinds, Richard |date=22 December 2017 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|2014\u201315 season]] saw record domestic cricket crowds in the states of [[South Australia]], [[New South Wales]], [[Tasmania]] and the [[Australian Capital Territory|ACT]], including a record attendance of 52,633 at the [[Adelaide Strikers]]' home semi-final, which was then the biggest ever crowd at the redeveloped [[Adelaide Oval]].<ref name=\"BBL5 schedule\" />\n\nIn the [[2015\u201316 Big Bash League season|2015\u201316 season]], attendance figure records continued to be broken across all the venues. [[Perth Scorchers]] became the first ever BBL team to sell out all of its home matches in a season.<ref>[http://www.perthscorchers.com.au/news/scorchers-set-league-sellout-record/2015-12-31 Scorchers Set League Sell-Out Record], perthscorchers.com.au. Retrieved on 12 January 2016</ref> On 2 January 2016, the BBL single match attendance record was surpassed, with a crowd of 80,883 watching the first of two Melbourne derbies between the [[Melbourne Stars]] and the [[Melbourne Renegades]] at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]]. The Big Bash League also entered the top 10 most attended sports leagues in the world with respect to average crowd per match in this season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstpost.com/sports/big-bash-league-2016-17-smashes-viewership-records-exceeds-expectations-3225952.html |title=Big Bash League 2016\u201317 smashes viewership records, exceeds expectations |work=Firstpost |date=29 January 2017 |accessdate=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Team\n! colspan=9 | Crowd average\n|-\n! [[2011\u201312 Big Bash League season|2011\u201312]]\n! [[2012\u201313 Big Bash League season|2012\u201313]]\n! [[2013\u201314 Big Bash League season|2013\u