 which was played at Metricon Stadium in Gold Coast and the other one at Ted Summerton Reserve in Moe.</ref> 21,541\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games, one of which was played at Metricon Stadium in Gold Coast and the other one at Ted Summerton Reserve in Moe.</ref> 21,447\n|- \n|align=left| [[Perth Scorchers]]\n| 14,905\n| 11,539\n| 17,380\n| 18,825\n| 20,273\n| 20,567\n| 21,511\n| 30,133\n| 26,586\n|- \n|align=left| [[Sydney Sixers]]\n| 20,068\n| 13,286\n| 19,914\n| 23,849\n| 27,956\n| 30,368\n| 24,815\n| 17,784\n| <ref>Includes one regular season home game played at C.ex Coffs International Stadium in Coffs Harbour.</ref> 15,327\n|-\n|align=left| [[Sydney Thunder]]\n| 18,423\n| 10,278\n| 14,866\n| 17,938\n| 19,333\n| 20,688\n| <ref>Includes one regular season home game played at Manuka Oval in Canberra where the attendance was 11,319, 27 January 2018, etc.</ref> 15,432\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games played at Manuka Oval in Canberra.</ref> 12,461\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games played at Manuka Oval in Canberra.</ref> 10,888\n|-\n|align=left| ''Finals''\n| 15,222\n| 17,568\n| 15,286\n| 27,920\n| 42,182\n| 25,642\n| 43,330\n| 22,854\n| 12,691\n|-\n| align=center|'''Whole season'''\n| '''18,021'''\n| '''14,883'''\n| '''18,778'''\n| '''23,590'''\n| '''29,443'''\n| '''30,114'''\n| '''26,531'''\n| '''20,552'''\n| '''18,353'''\n|}\n\n'''Notes'''\n\n===Television===\n\n====Australian television====\nBBL games are currently broadcast in Australia on free-to-air television by the [[Seven Network]] and subscription television by [[Fox Cricket]]. The [[Seven Network]] broadcasts 45 of 61 Matches including the Finals Series. [[Fox Cricket]] televises all 61 Matches including 16 Matches exclusively in 4K.<ref name=\"cricket 2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theroar.com.au/2018/04/13/foxtel-snatch-cricket-rights-from-nine-end-of-an-era/|title=End of an era confirmed: Foxtel and Seven snatch cricket rights from Nine|publisher=The Roar|first=Scott|last=Bailey|date=13 April 2018|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe rights were previously held by [[Network Ten|Network 10]], who in 2013 paid $100 million for BBL rights over five years, marking the channel's first foray in elite cricket coverage.<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/cricket/new-big-bash-league-broadcaster-channel-ten-thrilled-with-ratings-for-season-opening-derby/story-fni2usfi-1226788040468 New Big Bash League broadcaster Channel Ten thrilled with ratings for season opening derby] heraldsun.com.au. Retrieved on 25 November 2015.</ref>\n\nNetwork 10's BBL coverage became a regular feature of Australian summers and attracted an average audience of more than 943,000 people nationally in 2014\u201315 season, including a peak audience of 1.9 million viewers for the final between the Scorchers and Sixers.<ref>[http://www.cricket.com.au/news/bbl05-big-bash-league-fixture-release-2015-16-final-host-highest-qualifying-team-all-matches-live/2015-07-12 Big Bash League schedule released] cricket.com.au. Retrieved on 25 November 2015</ref>\n\nThe 2015\u201316 season attracted an average audience of 1.13 million for each match in Australia this season, an 18% increase on the previous season. A [[Audience measurement#GRPs/TRPs|cumulative audience]] of 9.65 million watched the matches in Australia, out of which 39% were females.<ref>[http://www.bigbash.com.au/news/kfc-big-bash-league-reaches-new-heights-in-bbl05-wbbl01-womens-big-bash/~/media/4AA18022BED84381B18846753425BC84.ashx Season Wrap \u2013 BBL|05] bigbash.com.au. Retrieved on 25 January 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.bigbash.com.au/news/kfc-big-bash-league-reaches-new-heights-in-bbl05-wbbl01-womens-big-bash/2016-01-25 BBL AND WBBL SOAR TO NEW HIGHS] bigbash.com.au. Retrieved on 25 January 2016</ref> The opening Sydney Derby match of the [[2015\u201316 Big Bash League season|season]] attracted a peak audience of 1.53 million.<ref>[http://www.bigbash.com.au/news/big-bash-league-tv-ratings-bbl-sydney-sixers-sydney-thunder/2015-12-18 #SydneySmash breaks ratings record] bigbash.com.au. Retrieved on 19 December 2015</ref> The last group match between [[Melbourne Renegades|Renegades]] and [[Adelaide Strikers|Strikers]] in Session 2 was watched by an average audience of 1.36 million, which peaked at 1.67 million.<ref>[https://twitter.com/malcolmconn/status/689335385575403520 Session 2: 1.36 mil Peak 1.67 mil Audience up 41% on 2014\u201315 Session 2 ave #BBL05] ''Malcolm Conn \u2013 Commercial Manager, Cricket Australia.'' Retrieved on 25 January 2016</ref> The BBL Final was watched by an average audience of 1.79 million, which peaked at 2.24 million viewers. This was the first time that the ratings for a BBL match crossed the 2 million mark.<ref>[https://twitter.com/malcolmconn/status/691391474928209920 SBIG ratings for BIG #BBL05 #BBLFinal! 1.79 mil watched @ThunderBBL win their first title. Peak 2.24 mil Audience up 17% 2015 final session 2] ''Malcolm Conn \u2013 Commercial Manager, Cricket Australia.'' Retrieved on 25 January 2016</ref>\n\n====Broadcast partners====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" | Countries \n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" | Network/s\n|-\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Australia]]\n|[[Fox Cricket]] (2011\u201313, 2018\u2013present)<br />[[Network Ten]] (2013\u20132018)<br />[[Seven Network]] (2018\u2013present)\n|-\n| {{flagicon|NZL}} [[New Zealand]]\n|[[Sky Sport (New Zealand)|Sky Sport]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|PAK}} [[Pakistan]]\n| [[PTV Sports]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|RSA}} [[South Africa]]\n|[[SuperSport (South African TV channel)|SuperSport]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|IND}} [[India]]\n| [[Sony ESPN]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SRI}} [[Sri Lanka]]\n| [[Sony Six|Sony SIX]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[United Kingdom]]\n| [[BT Sport]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[United States]]\n| [[Willow (TV channel)|Willow]] (2018\u2013present)<br />[[NBC Sports Gold]] (2018\u2013present)\n|-\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Canada]]\n| [[Commonwealth Broadcasting Network|CBN]] & [[ATN Cricket Plus]]</small><ref>{{cite press release|title=ATN Acquires Exclusive Canadian Broadcast Rights for Cricket from around the World|publisher=CNW|date=25 July 2016|url=http://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/atn-acquires-exclusive-canadian-broadcast-rights-for-cricket-from-around-the-world-588147782.html|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|RSA}} [[South Africa]]\n| [[SuperSport (South African TV channel)|Supersport]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|PNG}} [[Papua New Guinea]]\n| [[National Broadcasting Corporation of Papua New Guinea|NBC Papua New Guinea]]\n|-\n| South-East Asia\n| [[Fox Sports Asia]]\n|-\n| Central Asia\n|[[Sony Pictures Sports Network|SPN Sports India]]\n|-\n| Africa\n| [[Kwese Sports]]\n|-\n| The West Indies\n| [[Sports Max]]<br />[[Flow Sports]]\n|}\n\n==Grounds==\n{{See also|List of Big Bash League venues}}\nA total of seventeen grounds have been used to host BBL matches to date. [[Sydney Thunder]] moved out of [[ANZ Stadium]] after [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|2014\u201315 season]] and relocated to [[Sydney Showground Stadium]] for the next 10 years. From 2020, the tournament Final is played at the home ground of the team which wins 'The Qualifier', a finals match contested between the teams finishing 1st and 2nd in the League. The [[WACA Ground]] has hosted the final four times, more than any other venue. [[Manuka Oval]] hosted the final of [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|2014\u201315 BBL season]] as a [[neutral venue]] primarily because other major grounds were being prepared for the [[2015 Cricket World Cup]].<ref name=\"Manuka Oval venue\">[http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/big-bash/big-bash-league-final-at-manuka-oval-disappointing-for-perth-scorchers-fans-20150126-12y8ta.html Big Bash League final at Manuka Oval \"disappointing\" for Perth Scorchers fans] smh.com.au. Retrieved on 2 December 2015</ref>\n\n[[Optus Stadium]] replaced the WACA Ground as the home ground of [[Perth Scorchers]] commencing from the [[2017\u201318 Big Bash League season|2017\u201318 BBL]] semi-finals, where [[Perth]]'s home match against [[Hobart Hurricanes]] (and a doubleheader [[Women's Big Bash League|WBBL]] match featuring the [[Perth Scorchers (WBBL)|Perth Scorchers]] and [[Sydney Thunder (WBBL)|Sydney Thunder]]) became only the second public event at the new [[stadium]].\n\nIn September 2017 the [[Adelaide Strikers]] agreed to play one home BBL and [[Women's Big Bash League|WBBL]] match at [[Traeger Park]] in [[Alice Springs]] over the course of the 2017\u201318 season. In 2018, they announced that one BBL and two [[Women's Big Bash League|WBBL]] matches would be held at [[Traeger Park]] for the [[2018\u201319 Big Bash League season|2018\u201319]] and [[2019\u201320 Big Bash League season|2019\u201320]] seasons. Since [[2017\u201318 Big Bash League season|2017\u201318]], the [[Melbourne Renegades]] have played two matches per season at [[Kardinia Park]] in [[Geelong]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and the [[Hobart Hurricanes]] play multiple games at [[University of Tasmania Stadium|UTAS Stadium]] in [[Launceston, Tasmania|Launceston]], [[Tasmania]].\n\n{{wide image|Panoramic SCG BBL.jpg|1000px|align-cap=center|Panoramic view of the SCG during a Big Bash League match in 2011. It is the home ground of Sydney Sixers.}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" | Name of the stadium\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" | Capacity\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" | City\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" | Home team\n|- style=\"background:#cfc;\"\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| '''Current Grounds'''\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Adelaide Oval]] || 53,583 || [[Adelaide]] || [[Adelaide Strikers]] \n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Bellerive Oval|Blundstone Arena]] || 19,500 || [[Hobart]] || [[Hobart Hurricanes]] \n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Docklands Stadium|Marvel Stadium]] || 53,359 || [[Melbourne]] || [[Melbourne Renegades]] \n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Optus Stadium]] || 60,000 || [[Perth]] || [[Perth Scorchers]] \n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|[[The Gabba|Brisbane Cricket Ground]]|| 42,000 || [[Brisbane]] || [[Brisbane Heat]] \n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]] || 100,024 || [[Melbourne]] || [[Melbourne Stars]] \n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Sydney Showground Stadium]] || 22,000 || [[Sydney]] || [[Sydney Thunder]] \n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Sydney Cricket Ground]] || 48,000 || [[Sydney]] || [[Sydney Sixers]] \n|- style=\"background:#bbf;\"\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| '''Secondary Grounds'''\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[York Park|UTAS Stadium]] ||21,000|| [[Launceston, Tasmania|Launceston]] || [[Hobart Hurricanes]]\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Kardinia Park (stadium)|GMHBA Stadium]] ||34,000|| [[Geelong]] || [[Melbourne Renegades]]\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Traeger Park]] ||10,000 || [[Alice Springs]] || [[Adelaide Strikers]]\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Manuka Oval]] || 12,000 || [[Canberra]] ||[[Sydney Thunder]]\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Metricon Stadium]] || 25,000 || [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] || [[Brisbane Heat]]<br />[[Melbourne Stars]]\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Ted Summerton Reserve]] || 7,500 || [[Moe, Victoria|Moe]] || [[Melbourne Stars]]\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[Coffs Harbour International Stadium]] || 20,000 || [[Coffs Harbour]] || [[Sydney Sixers]]\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| '''Former Grounds'''\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[ANZ Stadium]] || 82,000 || [[Sydney]] || [[Sydney Thunder]] (2011\u20132014)\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| [[WACA Ground]] || 20,000 || [[Perth]] || [[Perth Scorchers]] (2011\u20132018)\n|-\n|}\n\n==Records and statistics==\n{{main|List of Big Bash League records and statistics}}\n[[File:Brisbane Heat vs Melbourne Stars T20 7.jpg|alt=|thumb|Chris Lynn, the leading run-scorer in BBL history]]\nHere is a list of Big Bash League records. All records are based on statistics at [[ESPNcricinfo|espncricinfo.com]].<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2014-15/engine/records/index.html?id=158;type=trophy Big Bash League/Records/Cup records] espncricinfo.com. Retrieved on 6 January 2015</ref> [[Brisbane Heat]] captain [[Chris Lynn]] currently holds the record of scoring most runs in the league.<ref name=\"most runs\" /> The record of taking most wickets in the league belongs to [[Ben Laughlin (cricketer)|Ben Laughlin]], who currently plays for [[Brisbane Heat]]. He has represented [[Hobart Hurricanes]] and [[Adelaide Strikers]] in the past, and has played a total of 88 BBL matches since 2011.<ref name=\"most wickets\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\"| Batting Records\n|-\n|Most runs\n|[[Brisbane Heat|{{color box|teal||}}]] [[Chris Lynn]]\n|2,332\n|-\n|[[batting average (cricket)|Highest average]]\n|[[Hobart Hurricanes|{{color box|purple}}]] [[D'Arcy Short]] \n|46.42\n|-\n|Highest score\n|[[Melbourne Stars|{{color box|#00B13F}}]] [[Marcus Stoinis]]\n|147* vs [[Sydney Sixers]] (12 January 2020)\n|-\n|Highest [[partnership (cricket)|partnership]]\n|[[Melbourne Stars|{{color box|#00B13F}}]] [[Marcus Stoinis]] & [[Hilton Cartwright]]\n|207 vs [[Sydney Sixers]] (12 January 2020)\n|-\n|Most sixes\n|[[Brisbane Heat|{{color box|teal}}]] [[Chris Lynn]]\n|146\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\"| Bowling Records\n|-\n|Most wickets\n|[[Brisbane Heat|{{color box|teal||}}]] [[Ben Laughlin (cricketer)|Ben Laughlin]]\n|110\n|-\n|[[Bowling average|Lowest average]]\n|[[Melbourne Stars|{{color box|#00B13F}}]] [[Lasith Malinga]]\n|15.00\n|-\n|Best [[strike rate]] \n|[[Sydney Thunder|{{colour box|#FF0090||}}]] [[Daniel Sams (cricketer)|Daniel Sams]]\n|13.5\n|-\n|Best [[economy rate]] \n|[[Melbourne Stars|{{color box|#00B13F}}]] [[Lasith Malinga]]\n|5.40\n|-\n|Best bowling figures\n|[[Melbourne Stars|{{color box|#00B13F}}]] [[Lasith Malinga]]\n|6/7 vs [[Perth Scorchers]] (12 December 2012)\n|-\n|Best bowling figures by a [[debutant]]\n|[[Sydney Thunder|{{colour box|#FF0090||}}]] [[Daniel Sams (cricketer)|Daniel Sams]]\n|4/14 vs [[Sydney Thunder]] (19 December 2017)\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\"| Fielding\n|-\n|Most dismissals ([[wicket-keeper]])\n|[[Brisbane Heat|{{color box|teal}}]] [[Jimmy Peirson]]\n|39\n|-\n|Most catches ([[fielding (cricket)|fielder]])\n|[[Melbourne Stars|{{color box|#00B13F}}]] [[Glenn Maxwell]]\n|50\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\"| Team Records\n|-\n|Highest total\n|[[Hobart Hurricanes|{{color box|purple}}]] [[Hobart Hurricanes]]\n|223\u20138 (20) vs [[Melbourne Renegades]] (12 January 2017)\n|-\n|Lowest total\n|[[Melbourne Renegades|{{color box|red}}]] [[Melbourne Renegades]]\n|57 (12.4) vs [[Melbourne Stars]] (3 January 2015)\n|-\n|}\n\n<sup>''Last updated on 28 February 2020''</sup>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cricket|Australia}}\n*[[List of Big Bash League records and statistics]]\n*[[List of Big Bash League centuries]]\n*[[Women's Big Bash League]]\n*[[The Big Appeal]]\n*[[Cricket Australia]]\n*[[Cricket in Australia]]\n*[[Indian Premier League]]\n*[[Pakistan Super League]]\n*[[Caribbean Premier League]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.bigbash.com.au/}}\n* [http://www.bigbash.com.au/fixtures#gender=men Schedule & Fixtures]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161022182557/http://cricketbadger.com/2016/09/bbl-india-stars-to-big-bash-in-wake-of-smriti-mandhana-to-heat/ World Cricket Badger]\n\n{{Big Bash League}}\n{{Big Bash League Cricket grounds}}\n{{Cricket in Australia}}\n{{Australian cricket season}}\n{{Twenty20 leagues}}\n{{Champions League Twenty20}}\n{{Sports leagues of Australia}}\n\n[[Category:Big Bash League| ]]\n[[Category:Australian domestic cricket competitions]]\n[[Category:Professional sports leagues in Australia]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Sports leagues established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Twenty20 cricket leagues]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 2011]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian professional Twenty20 cricket league}}\n{{Redirect|Big Bash|the competition run from 2005 to 2011|KFC Twenty20 Big Bash}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox cricket tournament main \n| name =  Big Bash League (BBL)\n| image = BBL Logo.png\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Official BBL Logo\n| country = [[Australia]]\n| administrator = [[Cricket Australia]]\n| cricket format = [[Twenty20]] \n| first = [[2011\u201312 Big Bash League season|2011\u201312]]\n| last = [[2019\u201320 Big Bash League season|2019\u201320]]\n| next =\n| tournament format = [[Round-robin tournament|Double round-robin]] and [[Single-elimination tournament|knockout finals]]\n| participants = [[#Current teams|8]]\n| matches = 59\n| champions = [[Sydney Sixers]] (2nd title)\n| most successful = [[Perth Scorchers]]<br />(3 titles)\n| most runs = [[Chris Lynn]] (2,332)<ref name=\"most runs\">{{cite web|title=Big Bash League / Records / Most runs|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=158;type=trophy|publisher=[[ESPNcricinfo]]|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref>\n| most wickets = [[Ben Laughlin (cricketer)|Ben Laughlin]] (110)<ref name=\"most wickets\">{{cite web|title=Big Bash League / Records / Most wickets|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2014-15/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=158;type=trophy|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref>\n| TV = [[Seven Network]]\n| website = [http://bigbash.com.au/ bigbash.com.au]\n| current =[[2019-20 Big Bash League season|2019\u201320]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Big Bash League''' ('''BBL''') is an Australian professional franchise [[Twenty20]] cricket league, which was established in 2011 by [[Cricket Australia]]. The Big Bash League replaced the previous competition, the [[KFC Twenty20 Big Bash]], and features eight city-based franchises instead of the six state teams which had participated previously. The competition has been sponsored by fast food chicken outlet [[KFC]] since its inception. It is one of the two T20 cricket leagues, alongside the [[Indian Premier League]], to feature amongst the [[List of sports attendance figures#Top 10 leagues in average attendance|top ten domestic sport leagues in average attendance]]. The winner of BBL|09 (2019/2020) was the [[Sydney Sixers]] who beat the [[Melbourne Stars]] by 19 runs in the final. The [[Sydney Sixers]] took the title from the [[Melbourne Renegades]] who beat the [[Melbourne Stars]] in the BBL|08 (2018/2019) final.\n\nBBL matches are played in Australia during the southern hemisphere summer, in the months of December, January and February.\n\nOut of the eight teams in the tournament, six have won the title at least once. The [[Perth Scorchers]] are the most successful team in the league's short history, winning the title three times including consecutively for two years and have reached the final of the tournament in five of the eight seasons. The other five teams which have won the title are the [[Adelaide Strikers]], [[Sydney Sixers]], [[Melbourne Renegades]], [[Brisbane Heat]] and [[Sydney Thunder]]. The current champions are the [[Sydney Sixers]] defeating the Melbourne Stars on 8 February 2020 at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]] in a game that was reduced to 12 overs each due to rain.\n\nBefore 2014, the top two teams in the tournament used to qualify for the [[Champions League Twenty20]] tournament. It was an annual international Twenty20 competition played between the top domestic teams from various nations, which became defunct after the 2014 tournament.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/898873.html |title=Champions League T20 discontinued |date=15 July 2015 |work=ESPN |accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Trophy===\nA design contest was held in 2011 to determine the design of the Big Bash League trophy. The competition was restricted to Australian designers, with the final design, chosen by the public from a field of three, revealed on 13 December 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bigbash.com.au/news-and-videos/article/2011-09/top-three-trophies-as-chosen-by-you |title=KFC T20 Big Bash League \u2013 Top three trophies as chosen by you |publisher=Bigbash.com.au |access-date=18 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608224315/http://www.bigbash.com.au/news-and-videos/article/2011-09/top-three-trophies-as-chosen-by-you |archive-date=8 June 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bigbash.com.au/news-and-videos/article/2011-12/the-trophy-has-been-revealed |title=KFC T20 Big Bash League \u2013 The trophy has been revealed |publisher=Bigbash.com.au }}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Expansion proposal===\n[[File:HobartVSPerth WACA.jpg|thumb|left|[[Perth Scorchers]] taking on [[Hobart Hurricanes]] at the [[WACA Ground|WACA]] in 2011]]\n\nIt had been proposed that the tournament would undergo expansion into more regional areas not supported by international cricket. The expansion was originally planned to be implemented in 2012. The proposed teams included: [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]], [[Canberra]], [[Geelong]], and [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]]. A [[New Zealand]]-based team was also mentioned as a possibility which would be based at [[Auckland]] or [[Christchurch]], but this is unlikely to happen.<ref name=\"CA consider expansion\">[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/cricket/cricket-australia-considering-big-bash-expansion/story-fn6w5lwh-1226242051179 Cricket Australia considering Big Bash expansion]. Retrieved 17 January 2012</ref><ref name=\"Fox Sports BBL expansion\">[http://www.foxsports.com.au/cricket/domestic-cricket/cricket-australia-looking-at-expanding-the-kfc-t20-big-bash-league-on-back-of-incredible-ratings-and-crowd-figures/story-fn5k3es5-1226242268221 Cricket Australia looks at expanding KFC T20 Big Bash League on back of incredible ratings and crowd figures]. Retrieved 17 January 2012</ref>  The expansion proposal was suspended, mainly because the proposed cities lacked the proper cricket hosting facilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsnewsfirst.com.au/articles/2012/01/27/big-bash-will-not-expand-next-year |title=Articles from January 27, 2012 |publisher=Sports News First |date=27 January 2012 |access-date=2 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231001806/http://www.sportsnewsfirst.com.au/articles/2012/01/27/big-bash-will-not-expand-next-year |archive-date=31 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kerry |first=Craig |url=http://www.theherald.com.au/news/local/news/general/newcastle-lacking-for-big-bash/2418587.aspx |title=Newcastle lacking for big bash |work=Newcastle Herald |date=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shane Warne MelbourneStars.jpg|thumb|[[Shane Warne]] bowling against Sydney Sixers in 2011 at the SCG]]\nIn 2015, former [[New Zealand national cricket team|Black Caps]] captain and [[Melbourne Stars]] coach [[Stephen Fleming]] suggested the expansion of the tournament to include New Zealand teams and become a trans-Tasman competition. He said an expansion into [[New Zealand]] would be widely supported by locals.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/expand-the-big-bash-league-to-new-zealand-stephen-fleming-says-20151204-glfjs7.html Expand the Big Bash League to New Zealand, says Stephen Fleming] smh.com.au. Retrieved on 4 December 2015</ref> His views were also supported by [[Brisbane Heat]] coach and former [[New Zealand national cricket team|Black Caps]] captain [[Daniel Vettori]].<ref>[http://www.bigbash.com.au/news/new-zealand-big-bash-league-team-mike-mckenna-daniel-vettori/2015-12-25 NEW ZEALAND COULD FIELD BBL TEAM: VETTORI] bigbash.com.au. Retrieved on 25 December 2015</ref> [[Melbourne Renegades]] chief executive Stuart Coventry also stated that he wants [[Cricket Australia]] to grant each club a fifth home fixture next season. Coventry said the BBL was ready to expand from 8 to 10 games, and adding matches would further establish the franchises.<ref>[http://www.perthnow.com.au/sport/cricket/big-bash-melbourne-renegades-boss-wants-more-games-next-season/news-story/6028af53f9ba88b7d40f55af9fc388b2 Big Bash: Melbourne Renegades boss wants more games next season] perthnow.com.au. Retrieved on 22 December 2015</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Anthony Everard, head of the BBL, flagged the league's intentions to approach expansion through a soft launch. He stated the short to medium term goal was to schedule BBL games involving existing franchises in regional markets before potentially adding new teams after the 2017\u201318 season when the broadcast deal expired. He also indicated the regional markets of [[Canberra]], [[Geelong]] and [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] will likely host games during the soft launch period.<ref name=\"regional areas\" /> On 27 January 2017, Everard announced an extra eight matches would be added to the 2017\u201318 season and implored each existing franchise to look at new markets when considering where the extra games would be played,<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/sport/cricket/big-bash-league-adds-eight-matches-as-expansion-plans-for-bbl-07-are-revealed-20170126-gtzph6.html Big Bash League adds eight matches, as expansion plans for BBL 07 are revealed]</ref> although the lengthened season was not implemented until 2018\u201319.\n\nIn 2018, it was reported that the Gold Coast Suns were interested in securing a Big Bash League franchise if the competition was expanded.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/afl/teams/gold-coast/the-gold-coast-suns-want-their-own-big-bash-league-franchise-when-the-competition-expands/news-story/7fdb9e0a829a58cdb6f51e016b85d998 |author=Hamilton, Andrew |title=The Gold Coast Suns want their own Big Bash League franchise when the competition expands |newspaper=The Courier Mail |date=30 April 2018 |accessdate=3 February 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===[[Women's Big Bash League]]===\n{{main|Women's Big Bash League}}\n\nFormer women's Test captain and Head of Brisbane's Centre of Excellence, [[Belinda Clark]], revealed on 19 January 2014 that planning for a women's BBL was in its early stages but could become a reality very soon. She stated that the proposal was being considered due to the huge rise in television ratings during the 2013\u201314 season, and the rise in [[women's cricket]] popularity.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8786049|title=Possibility of Women's Big Bash League|publisher=Ninemsn|date=19 January 2014|access-date=23 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201192919/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8786049|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 February 2015, [[Cricket Australia]] announced that a [[Women's Big Bash League|Women's Big Bash League (WBBL)]] would commence in the [[2015\u201316 Women's Big Bash League season|2015\u201316]] season, with teams aligned to the men's competition. It was announced that the teams would share the names and colours of the existing men's BBL teams, meaning that there would be two teams from [[Sydney]] and [[Melbourne]] and one team from [[Brisbane]], [[Perth]], [[Adelaide]] and [[Hobart]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cricket.com.au/news/womens-big-bash-league-to-align-with-mens-big-bash-league-clubs/2015-02-19|title=Eight teams announced for Women's BBL|publisher=cricket.com.au|date=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe inaugural [[Women's Big Bash League]] was won by the [[Sydney Thunder (WBBL)|Sydney Thunder]] against the [[Sydney Sixers (WBBL)|Sydney Sixers]]. The [[Sydney Thunder (WBBL)|Sydney Thunder]] won by 3 wickets. However WBBL 02 and 03 were won by the Sydney Sixers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/896429/scorecard/896551/sydney-sixers-women-vs-sydney-thunder-women-final/ |title=Final, Women's Big Bash League at Melbourne, Jan 24, 2016: Sydney Sixers Women v Sydney Thunder Women |work=ESPNCricInfo |accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Christmas Day match===\nIn December 2015, [[Cricket Australia]] revealed that they are looking into the possibility of hosting a [[Christmas|Christmas Day]] BBL match in the coming years, possibly after the next season. If the proposal is passed, it would be a first in the history of Australian sport since no professional matches are played in [[Australia]] on [[Christmas|Christmas Day]]. \"It is something we have just recently started discussing, the possibilities of that. We're talking about playing a Christmas Eve match, we already play Boxing Day,\" CA's Executive GM (Operations) Mike McKenna said.<ref>[http://www.bigbash.com.au/news/big-bash-league-to-investigate-possiblity-of-christmas-day-match/2015-12-21 BIG BASH LOOKS TO CHRISTMAS CLASH] bigbash.com.au. Retrieved on 22 December 2015</ref> This has not yet occurred, but in September 2018, it was reported that [[Cricket Australia]] had struck a deal with the Players Association to play BBL matches on Christmas Day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/cricket/domestic-cricket/big-bash/cricket-on-christmas-cricket-australia-strikes-secret-big-bash-league-deal-with-players/news-story/a9421a461f2beb20d45d88946f8f5bee|title=Cricket Australia, Christmas Day BBL, Big Bash League: CA \u2018reaches agreement with players\u2019 {{!}} Fox Sports|website=www.foxsports.com.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/players-agree-to-christmas-day-big-bash-report-20180928-p506ky.html|title=Players agree to Christmas Day Big Bash: report|date=2018-09-27|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref>\n\n==Tournament format==\n[[File:Ben Cutting GABBA.jpg|thumb|[[Ben Cutting]] of [[Brisbane Heat]] batting against [[Melbourne Stars]] in 2014]]\nSince the inception of the BBL in 2011, the tournament has followed the same format every year except the inaugural season.<ref name=\"BBL format\" /> The [[2011\u201312 Big Bash League season|first BBL season]] had 28 group stage matches, before expanding to 32 in the following season.<ref name=\"regional areas\">[http://www.bigbash.com.au/news/big-bash-may-head-to-regional-areas-cricket-australia-geelong-canberra-gold-coast/2016-01-03 Big Bash May Head to Regional Areas], bigbash.com.au. Retrieved on 6 January 2016</ref>\n\nSince the 2018\u201319 season, each team plays all other teams twice during a season, for a total of 56 regular season matches before the finals series.\n\nIn previous seasons of the tournament, the group stage matches were divided into eight rounds, with four matches played in each round. Each team played six other teams once during a season, and one team twice. This allowed for both Sydney and Melbourne (which have two teams each) to play 2 [[derbies]] within a single season.<ref name=\"total games\">[http://www.theroar.com.au/2015/01/27/whats-next-big-bash-league-since-asked/ What's next for the Big Bash League? Since you asked\u2026] theroar.com.au. Retrieved on 4 December 2015</ref> Each team played eight group stage matches, four at home and four away, before the top four ranked teams progressed to the semi finals.<ref name=\"total games\" /> In the 2017/18 Season, the format changed so that there would be 40 group stage matches with each team playing 10 matches before the semi finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bigbash.com.au/news/big-bash-league-expansion-bbl07-extra-matches-anthony-everard-new-venues-stars-scorchers-sixers/2017-01-27 |title=BBL set for more games, new venues |work=BigBash.com.au |publisher=Cricket Australia |date=27 January 2017 |accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref> The season was held over a similar time-frame thus resulting in more doubleheaders (one game afternoon, one game night) and teams playing more regularly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bigbash.com.au/fixtures|title=Upcoming Matches |work=bigbash.com.au |accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe final of the tournament is played at the home ground of the highest-ranked team. The only exception to this rule was [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|2014\u201315 season]] when the final was played at a neutral venue ([[Manuka Oval]]), due to the [[2015 Cricket World Cup]].<ref name=\"BBL format\">[http://www.cricketmad.com/category/cricket-latest-news/big-bash-league-2015-16-schedule-20151202-0003/ Big Bash League 2015\u201316 schedule \u2013 Tournament kick-starts on December 17] cricketmad.com. Retrieved on 4 December 2015</ref><ref name=\"Manuka Oval venue\"/>\n\nIn the 2018\u201319 season, the league introduced a 'bat flip' (instead of a coin toss) to decide who would bat/bowl first.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/coin-toss-removed-bat-flip-bbl-big-bash-league/2018-12-11 |title=No more coin toss in BBL shake-up |website=Cricket.com.au |date=11 December 2018 |accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Current teams==\nThe competition features eight city-based franchises, instead of the [[Sheffield Shield#Teams|six state-based teams]] which had previously competed in the KFC Twenty20 Big Bash. Each state's capital city features one team, with [[Sydney]] and [[Melbourne]] featuring two. The team names and colours for all teams were officially announced on 6 April 2011.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/australia/content/story/509663.html New look and feel for freshly formed Big Bash teams], ESPNcricinfo. Retrieved 22 April 2011.</ref> The Melbourne Derby and Sydney Derby matches are some of the most heavily attended matches during the league and are widely anticipated by the fans.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/sport/cricket/bbl-big-derbies-to-feature-as-big-bash-league-draw-released/news-story/0ad028fc0197687ea1d658c2fdc68b7d Big Bash League: double-headers, derbies, big egos all on show in 2015\u201316 version of BBL] news.com.au. Retrieved on 4 December 2015</ref> The [[Perth Scorchers|Scorchers]] and [[Sydney Sixers|Sixers]] have also developed a rivalry between them over the years and their matches attract good crowds and TV ratings.<ref>[http://www.sportsbanter.com.au/bbl04-round-3-preview-sydney-sixers-v-perth-scorchers/ Sydney Sixers v Perth Scorchers]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} sportsbanter.com.au. Retrieved on 4 December 2015</ref>\n\nA single city-based franchise can have a maximum of 18 contracted players for a season, with the squad including a minimum of two rookie contracts and a maximum of six overseas players, although only two international players can play in each match. Each team can also have a maximum of two overseas replacement players, in case the original overseas players get injured or withdraw.<ref name=\"cricketbadger1\">[http://cricketbadger.com/2015/02/bbl05-contracting-for-the-next-big-bash-league-begins/ BBL|05: Contracting for the next Big Bash League begins] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208093202/http://cricketbadger.com/2015/02/bbl05-contracting-for-the-next-big-bash-league-begins/ |date=8 December 2015 }} cricketbadger.com. Retrieved on 2 December 2015</ref>\n\n{{Location map+|Australia|width=350|float=center|caption=Location of Big Bash League teams|places=\n {{Location map~|Australia|lat_deg=-31|lat_min=-58|lon_deg=115|lon_min=51|position=right|background=|mark=Orange pog.svg|label=[[Perth Scorchers|Scorchers]]|label_size=100}}\n {{Location map~|Australia|lat_deg=-34|lat_min=-52|lon_deg=138|lon_min=29|position=left|background=|mark=Blue pog.svg|label=[[Adelaide Strikers|Strikers]]|label_size=100}}\n {{Location map~|Australia|lat_deg=-27|lat_min=-29|lon_deg=153|lon_min=33|position=left|background=|mark=Cyan pog.svg|label=[[Brisbane Heat|Heat]]|label_size=100}}\n {{Location map~|Australia|lat_deg=-42|lat_min=-52|lon_deg=147|lon_min=22|position=left|background=|mark=Purple pog.svg|label=[[Hobart Hurricanes|Hurricanes]]|label_size=100}}\n {{Location map~|Australia|lat_deg=-37|lat_min=-49|lon_deg=144|lon_min=49|position=left|background=|mark=Green pog.svg|label=[[Melbourne Stars|Stars]]|label_size=100}}\n {{Location map~|Australia|lat_deg=-37|lat_min=-49|lon_deg=144|lon_min=90|position=right|background=|mark=Red pog.svg|label=[[Melbourne Renegades|Renegades]]|label_size=100}}\n {{Location map~|Australia|lat_deg=-33|lat_min=-53|lon_deg=151|lon_min=13|position=top|background=|mark=DeepPink pog.svg|label=[[Sydney Sixers|Sixers]]|label_size=100}}\n {{Location map~|Australia|lat_deg=-33|lat_min=-51|lon_deg=150|lon_min=33|position=left|background=|mark=SpringGreen pog.svg|label=[[Sydney Thunder|Thunder]]|label_size=100}}\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! \n! Team\n! Colour\n! City\n! State\n! Home ground\n! Coach\n! Captain(s)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#009FDF;\"|\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Adelaide Strikers]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | Blue\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Adelaide]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[South Australia]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Adelaide Oval]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Jason Gillespie]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Travis Head]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#00C1C1;\"|\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Brisbane Heat]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | Teal\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Brisbane]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Queensland]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[The Gabba|Brisbane Cricket Ground]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Darren Lehmann]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Chris Lynn]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#69359C;\"|\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Hobart Hurricanes]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | Purple\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Hobart]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Tasmania]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Bellerive Oval]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Adam Griffith]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Matthew Wade]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:red;\"|\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Melbourne Renegades]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | Red\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Melbourne]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Docklands Stadium]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Michael Klinger]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Aaron Finch]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#00B13F;\"|\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Melbourne Stars]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | Dark green\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Melbourne]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[David Hussey]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Glenn Maxwell]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ff8000;\"|\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Perth Scorchers]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | Orange\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Perth]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Western Australia]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Perth Stadium]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Adam Voges]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Mitchell Marsh]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FF0090;\"|\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Sydney Sixers]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | Magenta\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Sydney]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[New South Wales]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Sydney Cricket Ground]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Greg Shipperd]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | [[Moises Henriques]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#96D701;\"|\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Sydney Thunder]]\n| style=\"background:white;\" | Lime green\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Sydney]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[New South Wales]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Sydney Showground Stadium]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Shane Bond]]\n| style=\"background: #eee;\" | [[Callum Ferguson]]\n|}\n\n==Tournament results==\nOut of the eight teams in the tournament, six have won the title at least once. The [[Perth Scorchers]] are the most successful team, winning the title three times (including back-to-back wins in 2013\u201314 and 2014\u201315).<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2015-16/engine/records/team/series_results.html?id=158;type=trophy Big Bash League / Records / Series results] espncricinfo.com. Retrieved on 4 December 2015</ref> Perth have also reached the final of the tournament the most times (including consecutive appearances in the first four seasons). The Sydney Sixers have won the tournament twice, both in the inaugural season (2011\u201312) and the most recent season (2019\u201320). Only two other teams (the Hobart Hurricanes and Melbourne Stars) have reached the final at least twice<ref name=\"espncricinfo1\">{{cite news |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/kpl-14/engine/records/team/series_results.html?class=6;id=4846;type=team |title=Perth Scorchers / Records / Twenty20 matches |date= |work=ESPN |accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref> The other four teams which have won the title once are the [[Brisbane Heat]] in the second season (2012\u201313), the [[Sydney Thunder]] in 2015\u201316,<ref name=\"espncricinfo2\">[http://www.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2011/engine/series/509666.html Big Bash League 2011\u201312] espncricinfo.com. Retrieved on 2 December 2015.</ref><ref name=\"espncricinfo3\">[http://www.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2012/engine/series/571220.html Big Bash League 2012\u201313] espncricinfo.com. Retrieved on 2 December 2015.</ref> the [[Adelaide Strikers]] in 2017\u201318,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8044/scorecard/1114898 |title=Scorecard: Final, Big Bash League at Adelaide, Feb 4, 2018 |work=ESPNCricInfo|accessdate=17 February 2019}}</ref> and the [[Melbourne Renegades]] in 2018\u201319.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8044/game/1152569/tbc-vs-tbc-final-big-bash-league-2018 |title= Scorecard: Final, Big Bash League at Melbourne, Feb 17, 2019 |work=ESPNCricInfo|accessdate=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[WACA Ground]] has hosted the final on four occasions, the most of any venue.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; width:100%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" |Season\n!colspan=3 style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" |Final\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" |Final host\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" |Final venue\n|-\n! style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" |Winner\n! style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" |Result\n! style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" |Runner-up\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n|2011\u201312<br />''[[2011\u201312 Big Bash League season|Details]]''\n|[[Sydney Sixers]]<br /><small>3/158 (18.5 overs)</small>\n|'''Sixers won by 7 wickets'''<br />[http://www.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2011/engine/match/524945.html Scorecard]\n|[[Perth Scorchers]]<br /><small>5/156 (20 overs)</small>\n|[[Perth Scorchers]]\n|[[WACA Ground]]\n|- style=\"background:white;\n|2012\u201313<br />''[[2012\u201313 Big Bash League season|Details]]''\n|[[Brisbane Heat]]<br /><small>5/167 (20 overs)</small>\n|'''Heat won by 34 runs'''<br />[http://www.espncricinfo.com/australia-domestic-2012/engine/current/match/571266.html Scorecard]\n|[[Perth Scorchers]]<br /><small>9/133 (20 overs)</small>\n|[[Perth Scorchers]]\n|[[WACA Ground]]\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\n|2013\u201314<br />''[[2013\u201314 Big Bash League season|Details]]''\n|[[Perth Scorchers]]<br /><small>4/191 (20 overs)</small>\n|'''Scorchers won by 39 runs'''<br />[http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/654099.html Scorecard]\n|[[Hobart Hurricanes]]<br /><small>7/152 (20 overs)</small>\n|[[Perth Scorchers]]\n|[[WACA Ground]]\n|- style=\"background:white;\n|2014\u201315<br />''[[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|Details]]''\n|[[Perth Scorchers]]<br /><small>6/148 (20 overs)</small>\n|'''Scorchers won by 4 wickets'''<br />[http://www.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2014-15/engine/match/756803.html Scorecard]\n|[[Sydney Sixers]]<br /><small>5/147 (20 overs)</small>\n|[[Canberra]]/[[Perth Scorchers]]\n|[[Manuka Oval]]\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\n|2015\u201316<br />''[[2015\u201316 Big Bash League season|Details]]''\n|[[Sydney Thunder]]<br /><small>7/181 (19.3 overs)</small>\n|'''Thunder won by 3 wickets'''<br />[http://www.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2015-16/engine/current/match/897763.html Scorecard]\n|[[Melbourne Stars]]<br /><small>9/176 (20 overs)</small>\n|[[Melbourne Stars]]\n|[[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n|-\n|2016\u201317<br />''[[2016\u201317 Big Bash League season|Details]]''\n|[[Perth Scorchers]]<br /><small> 1/144 (15.5 overs)</small>\n|'''Scorchers won by 9 wickets'''<br />[http://www.espncricinfo.com/big-bash-league-2016-17/engine/match/1023649.html Scorecard]\n|[[Sydney Sixers]]<br /><small>9/141 (20 overs)</small>\n|[[Perth Scorchers]]\n|[[WACA Ground]]\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\n|2017\u201318<br />''[[2017\u201318 Big Bash League season|Details]]''\n|[[Adelaide Strikers]]<br /><small> 2/202 (20 overs)</small>\n|'''Strikers won by 25 runs'''<br />[http://www.es